    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2022-March/020057.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The context discusses various proposals related to Bitcoin transactions and the use of oracles to execute them. One proposal involves a company offering liquidity as a service, which would require users to pay a monthly fee even if they are not using the service. Another proposal involves the use of PTLCs, which allow for non-interactive settlement during escrow transactions, making it easier for developers to create applications with better user experiences. Additionally, the context explores the idea of creating pre-approved lines of credit from a Bitcoin wallet that can be drawn down with oracle attestations. This scheme has multiple potential applications, including commissioning work from an unbranded workperson.The email conversation also mentions DLCs, which can be used for recurring subscriptions without requiring an on-chain transaction. DLCs allow providers to specify how much they can withdraw, ensuring that they cannot withdraw more or less than authorized. Furthermore, the context highlights the benefits of PTLCs over escrow providers in terms of non-interactive settlement and reduced bi-directional communication requirements. The conversation also touches on the issue of interactiveness at settlement time for multisig and the challenges it poses for developers. Finally, the email discusses the possibility of implementing multiple PTLCs triggered by a single oracle and reducing interactiveness requirements for new bitcoin applications to improve user experience. There is also a link to a GitHub repository containing an old Python sapio contract that allows for cancellable subscriptions, which function as a time-based autopay scheme.</summary>
